`AuthStorageService.listAccounts()` (`services/AuthStorageService.ts:98`) does a fresh `localStorage.getItem` + `JSON.parse` + array scan on **every** call. It's the backing call for `getActiveAccount()` and `findByUsername()`, and every scene independently calls `getActiveAccount()` on entry:

```
scenes/Gameplay.ts:92    create() → getActiveAccount()
scenes/Gameplay.ts:402   completeLevel() → getActiveAccount() again
scenes/IntroCharacter.ts:69
scenes/LevelSelect.ts:28
scenes/Result.ts:37
```

Same pattern for `ProgressStorageService.getProgress()` (`services/ProgressStorageService.ts:79`) — parsed fresh in `LevelSelect.create()`, again in `hasSeenIntro()`, again inside `recordLevelResult()`, again in `Result.ts:38`, each a full JSON.parse of the whole progress object just to read one field.

With today's tiny account count this costs nothing, but it's the wrong pattern to build on — add more accounts/levels later and it scales linearly per read. Fix: cache the active account/progress in memory for the life of the session, invalidate on write.

```typescript
// AuthStorageService.ts
let cachedAccounts: LocalAccount[] | null = null;

function invalidateCache(): void { cachedAccounts = null; }

listAccounts(): LocalAccount[] {
    if (cachedAccounts) return cachedAccounts;
    const raw = safeGet(KEYS.accounts);
    if (!raw) return (cachedAccounts = []);
    try {
        const parsed: unknown = JSON.parse(raw);
        cachedAccounts = Array.isArray(parsed) ? parsed.filter(isAccount) : [];
    } catch { cachedAccounts = []; }
    return cachedAccounts;
},
// call invalidateCache() after register()'s safeSet(KEYS.accounts, ...)
```

Same idea for `ProgressStorageService`: keep one in-memory `LocalProgress` per `accountId` for the scene's lifetime instead of re-reading in `hasSeenIntro` right after `create()` already loaded it.

`Gameplay.update()` runs every frame while `state === 'EXPLORE'` and calls `updateMarkerAndAction()` (`scenes/Gameplay.ts:271`), which calls `currentTarget()` → `nextInteraction()` (`scenes/Gameplay.ts:258-263`):

```typescript
private nextInteraction(): InteractionDefinition | null {
    const pending = this.segment.interactions
        .filter((i) => !this.resolvedIds.has(i.id))
        .sort((a, b) => a.order - b.order);
    return pending[0] ?? null;
}
```

This `.filter().sort()` runs at 60fps even though `resolvedIds` only changes when the player resolves an interaction (`resolveInteraction`, `Gameplay.ts:366`) or a segment rebuilds (`buildSegment`). Cache it and invalidate on those two events instead:

```typescript
private pendingCache: InteractionDefinition[] | null = null;

private invalidatePending(): void { this.pendingCache = null; }

private nextInteraction(): InteractionDefinition | null {
    if (!this.pendingCache) {
        this.pendingCache = [...this.segment.interactions]
            .filter((i) => !this.resolvedIds.has(i.id))
            .sort((a, b) => a.order - b.order);
    }
    return this.pendingCache[0] ?? null;
}
// call this.invalidatePending() in resolveInteraction() and buildSegment()
```

Also in `updateMarkerAndAction()` (`Gameplay.ts:283`), this line is dead code — the ternary evaluates to `0` on both branches, so it's computed every frame for nothing:

```typescript
if (Math.abs((this.marker.y - (this.markerTween?.isPlaying() ? 0 : 0)) - target.markerY) > 20) {
```

Simplify to `Math.abs(this.marker.y - target.markerY) > 20`.

